\title{Some observations regarding the correct form of the conservation law for main-chain polymer nematics}



\author{Daniel Sven\v sek}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Faculty of Mathematics and Physics, University of Ljubljana, Jadranska 19, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia}



\author{Rudolf Podgornik}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Faculty of Mathematics and Physics, University of Ljubljana, Jadranska 19, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia}
\affiliation{Department of Theoretical Physics, J. Stefan Institute, Jamova 39,  SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia}
\affiliation{Department of Physics,  University of Massachusetts, Amherst MA 01003, USA}

\begin{abstract}
We explore the implications of the conservation law and the corresponding ``continuity equation",  resulting from the coupling between the positional and orientational order in main-chain polymer nematics, by showing that the vectorial and tensorial forms of this equation are in general not equivalent, neither are they disjoint alternatives. We analyze the relation between one and the other and point to the fundamental role of chain backfolding determining their relative strength. 
Finally we show that the correct penalty potential in the free energy, implementing this conservation law, should actually connect both the tensorial and the vectorial constraints. The consequences of the connectivity of the main-chain polymer nematics for their mesoscopic description are thus highly non-trivial. 
\end{abstract}

\pacs{61.30.Vx, 61.41.+e, 61.30.Dk, 87.14.gk}


